 television series]]\n[[Category:American television spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Chicago (franchise)]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Chicago Police Department]]\n[[Category:NBC original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by Universal Television]]\n[[Category:Television series by Wolf Films]]\n[[Category:Television series created by Dick Wolf]]\n[[Category:Television shows featuring audio description]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Chicago]]\n", "name_user": "FeverishAxe0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_P.D._(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Graham Rathbone", "text_new": "{{short description|Welsh footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Graham Rathbone\n| image               = \n| fullname            = Graham Rathbone\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1942|8|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Wales\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2012|1|8|1942|8|22|df=y}}<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\"/>\n| death_place = [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Wales\n| height              = \n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Central Defender]]\n| youthyears1         = {{0|0000}}\u20131960\n| youthclubs1         = [[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]]\n| years1              = 1960\u20131966\n| clubs1              = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| caps1               = 191\n| goals1              = 7\n| years2              = 1966\u20131973\n| clubs2              = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n| caps2               = 233\n| goals2              = 11\n| years3              = 1973\u20131974\n| clubs3              = [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]]\n| caps3               = 36\n| goals3              = 0\n| years4              = 1974\u2013?\n| clubs4              = [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]\n| caps4               = \n| goals4              =\n| nationalyears1 =         \n| nationalteam1 =          \n| nationalcaps1 =     \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update            = \n| ntupdate            = \n}}\n\n'''Graham Rathbone''' (22 August 1942 \u2013 8 January 2012) was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] professional footballer.<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\"/>\n\nRathbone was born in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]].  A centre-half, he began his career with [[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]]. In 1960, he joined [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] and made 191 appearances for the club, scoring 7 goals. In 1966 manager [[Jimmy McGuigan]] signed him at [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] for a \u00a310,000 fee<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\"/> where he made 233 appearances before moving to [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] and [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]].<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\"/><ref>[http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/newport/newport.html Newport County A-Z of transfers]</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Grimsby Town===\n[[Football League Fourth Division|Division Four]]: Champions [[1971\u201372 in English football|1971\u201372]]<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/story-14379712-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505143617/http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/story-14379712-detail/story.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |newspaper=Grimsby Telegraph |title=Grimsby Town: Graham Rathbone dies following illness |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rathbone, Graham}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Newport, Wales]]\n[[Category:Merthyr Tydfil F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newport County A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grimsby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cambridge United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kettering Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{Wales-footy-defender-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name               = Graham Rathbone\n| image               = \n| fullname            = Graham Rathbone\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1942|8|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Wales\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2012|1|8|1942|8|22|df=y}}<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\"/>\n| death_place = [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], Wales\n| height              = \n| position            = [[Defender (association football)|Central Defender]]\n| youthyears1         = {{0|0000}}\u20131960\n| youthclubs1         = [[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]]\n| years1              = 1960\u20131966\n| clubs1              = [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]]\n| caps1               = 191\n| goals1              = 7\n| years2              = 1966\u20131973\n| clubs2              = [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n| caps2               = 233\n| goals2              = 11\n| years3              = 1973\u20131974\n| clubs3              = [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]]\n| caps3               = 36\n| goals3              = 0\n| years4              = 1974\u2013?\n| clubs4              = [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]]\n| caps4               = \n| goals4              =\n| nationalyears1 =         \n| nationalteam1 =          \n| nationalcaps1 =     \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update            = \n| ntupdate            = \n}}\n\n'''Graham Rathbone''' (22 August 1942 \u2013 8 January 2012) was a [[Welsh people|Welsh]] professional footballer.<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\"/>\n\nRathbone was born in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]].  A centre-half, he began his career with [[Merthyr Tydfil F.C.|Merthyr Tydfil]]. In 1960, he joined [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]] and made 191 appearances for the club, scoring 7 goals. In 1966 manager [[Jimmy McGuigan]] signed him at [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] for a \u00a310,000 fee<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\"/> where he made 233 appearances before moving to [[Cambridge United F.C.|Cambridge United]] and [[Kettering Town F.C.|Kettering Town]].<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\"/><ref>[http://www.neilbrown.newcastlefans.com/newport/newport.html Newport County A-Z of transfers]</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Grimsby Town===\n[[Football League Fourth Division|Division Four]]: Champions [[1971\u201372 in English football|1971\u201372]]<ref name=\"Graham Rathbone\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/story-14379712-detail/story.html |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130505143617/http://www.thisisgrimsby.co.uk/story-14379712-detail/story.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=5 May 2013 |newspaper=Grimsby Telegraph |title=Grimsby Town: Graham Rathbone dies following illness |date=10 January 2012 |accessdate=13 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rathbone, Graham}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Welsh footballers]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Newport, Wales]]\n[[Category:Merthyr Tydfil F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Newport County A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Grimsby Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Cambridge United F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Kettering Town F.C. players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n\n\n{{Wales-footy-defender-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Red Director", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"Welsh footballer\", overriding Wikidata description \"Welsh footballer\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graham_Rathbone"}
{"title_page": "Nemone", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_name    = Nemone Metaxas\n| name          = Nemone\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|11|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]], England\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   = \n| years_active   = 1996\u2013present\n| occupation    = Radio presenter, disc jockey, television presenter/producer\n| spouse        =\n| alma_mater    = [[Victoria University of Manchester]]\n| other_names   = Nemone\n| education     = B.S. Psychology\n| nationality   = British\n| children      = Daughter, Ella, born July 2009\n}}\n'''Nemone Metaxas''' (born 3 November 1972 in [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/6music/shows/nemone/biography|title=BBC \u2013 6 Music \u2013 Nemone \u2013 Biography|work=BBC}}</ref> often billed simply as '''Nemone''', is an English DJ, radio presenter, television presenter/producer and former [[track and field]] athlete.\n\nHer father's Greek ancestral village is in Sekhia and the family name is Anastasakis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/olympics/2383858/Athletics-An-unlikely-odyssey-from-Ash-to-Athens.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|title=Athletics: An unlikely odyssey from Ash to Athens|first=Robert|last=Philip|date=31 July 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting career==\nAfter finishing her degree in [[psychology]] at the [[Victoria University of Manchester]] in 1995,<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.manchester.ac.uk/undergraduate/ourreputation/distinguishedalumni/nemonemetaxas|work=University of Manchester website|title=Nemone Metaxas|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925224859/http://www.manchester.ac.uk/undergraduate/ourreputation/distinguishedalumni/nemonemetaxas|archive-date=25 September 2008}}</ref> Nemone worked as a [[research assistant]] in a [[psychiatric ward]]. She went on to become a receptionist at [[Kiss 102]] in Manchester. In 1997, she became the presenter and producer of ''The Word'' radio programme as [[Kiss 105]] went on the air. She subsequently presented [[Capital Manchester|Galaxy 102]] FM's Morning Show, Network Chill Out Show and The [[Galaxy Radio|Galaxy]] Chart for [[Manchester]]. She left as anchor of the Morning Show for a job at BBC Radio 1.\n \nNemone joined [[BBC Radio 1]] in October 2000 initially hosting the Saturday breakfast show. She filled in for [[Jo Whiley]]'s weekday morning show in 2001 while Whiley was on maternity leave. She then took the weekend afternoon slot which she hosted from Autumn 2001 through to the end of 2003.\n\nAfter a revamp of the Radio 1 daytime schedule from early 2004, Nemone replaced [[Scott Mills]] on the overnight show (4{{nbsp}}am{{snd}}7{{nbsp}}am) broadcasting to audiences in excess of 3 million. She left Radio 1 in September 2005; [[JK and Joel]] (Monday-Thursday) and [[Fearne Cotton]] and [[Reggie Yates]] (Friday) took over her early morning slot.\n\nShe joined [[BBC Radio 6 Music]] on 3 October 2005, she began presenting the ''[[Dream Ticket]]'' show as well as filling in on 6 Music's drive time show when [[Steve Lamacq]] was away.\n\nNemone took over [[Vic McGlynn]]'s weekday lunchtime show, weekdays in the 3{{snd}}4{{nbsp}}pm slot on 4 September 2006. She could also be heard covering various shows on [[BBC Radio 2]].\n\n[[Cerys Matthews]] filled in for her after she began six months maternity leave on 6 July 2009. After Matthews herself went on maternity leave on 24 November, the show was presented by either [[Chris Hawkins]] or [[Andrew Collins (broadcaster)|Andrew Collins]]. In July 2009, Nemone gave birth to a baby girl and returned to the station on 1 February 2010.\n\nWhen pregnant with her second child in 2011, she moved from weekdays taking over the weekend breakfast show.  After a short maternity leave she returned, steering it to record RAJAR figures.\n\nThe requirement to take the show to Media City in Salford meant Nemone passing on the opportunity of returning to Manchester; electing to stay in London where she had established her young family.\n\nIn April 2013 Nemone fulfilled a lifelong ambition to curate a specialist dance and electronic music show on BBC Radio 6 Music \u2013 ''Nemone's Electric Ladyland''. She runs a club night in West London.\n\nShe participated with her daughter in the Bumps & Babies Mile in [[Battersea Park]] for [[Sport Relief 2010]] along with [[Denise Van Outen]], [[Carly Cole]], [[Gail Emms]], [[Natasha Kaplinsky]] and [[Kim Medcalf]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sportrelief/news/180210_bumpsbabies.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 Sport Relief \u2013 Bumps and Babies Mile|work=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/02/19/bump-in-the-white-115875-22053881/|title=Carly Zucker joins Denise Van Outen on Sports Relief Bumps and Babies Mile in London|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Television career==\nNemone co-hosted the [[BBC One]] television programme ''[[101 Ways to Leave a Gameshow]]'' alongside [[Steve Jones (Welsh presenter)|Steve Jones]]. She was seen describing the method of eviction from the game show and then interviewing the losing contestants.\n\nNemone was one of the contestants on ''[[Celebrity Mastermind]]'' aired on 20 August 2017 on BBC One. Her specialist subject was the children's books of [[Roald Dahl]], and she came 2nd in the show.\n\n==Musical career==\nNemone is an accomplished musician. She was singer and saxophonist in a [[funk]] band \u2013 other members being Tom Findlay (who went on to form [[Groove Armada]]),<ref>stated by Nemone, herself, on-air, The Dream Ticket show, 19 January 2006.</ref> Andy Spence from NYPC, and Perrier Award-winning comedian [[Dan Antopolski]].\n\n==Athletic career==\nApart from radio and TV broadcasting, Nemone is also a keen athlete. Nemone is a former champion [[400 metres]] runner. In 1999 she won the Greater Manchester Championships. In 2000 she qualified for the British Championships, and competed in the 400m British Olympic trials.\n\nNemone decided to bid to run for the Greek Olympic team for the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]. Her training was filmed for the [[BBC Three]] television programme ''My Big Fat Greek Olympic Dream''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/4a5d9f9462224e68885bcc9213d6550c|work=BBC website|title=My Big Fat Greek Olympic Dream|date=1 August 2004}}</ref> She has competed in triathlons, most notably finishing in the top 20 amateur women in the 2006 London Triathlon.\n\nAlso, on screen, Nemone has hosted the [[X Games]] in Barcelona and Ski Sunday in [[Livigno]] for the television show ''[[Grandstand (TV series)|Grandstand]]''.\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Honeyball, Lee,[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,502093,00.html \"My team : Radio 1 DJ Nemone Metaxas on Sale Harriers Athletics Club\"], [[The Observer]] Sport Monthly, Sunday 3 June 2001\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=2932430|name=Nemone}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s9ky3 ''Nemone's Electric Ladyland''] (BBC Radio 6 Music)\n\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English radio DJs]]\n[[Category:People from Chester]]\n[[Category:English people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 1 presenters]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 2 presenters]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 6 Music presenters]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=October 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| birth_name    = Nemone Metaxas\n| name          = Nemone\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1972|11|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]], England\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   = \n| years_active   = 1996\u2013present\n| occupation    = Radio presenter, disc jockey, television presenter/producer\n| spouse        =\n| alma_mater    = [[Victoria University of Manchester]]\n| other_names   = Nemone\n| education     = B.S. Psychology\n| nationality   = British\n| children      = Daughter, Ella, born July 2009\n}}\n'''Nemone Metaxas''' (born 3 November 1972 in [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/6music/shows/nemone/biography|title=BBC \u2013 6 Music \u2013 Nemone \u2013 Biography|work=BBC}}</ref> often billed simply as '''Nemone''', is an English DJ, radio presenter, television presenter/producer and former [[track and field]] athlete.\n\nHer father's Greek ancestral village is in Sekhia and the family name is Anastasakis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/olympics/2383858/Athletics-An-unlikely-odyssey-from-Ash-to-Athens.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|title=Athletics: An unlikely odyssey from Ash to Athens|first=Robert|last=Philip|date=31 July 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcasting career==\nAfter finishing her degree in [[psychology]] at the [[Victoria University of Manchester]] in 1995,<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.manchester.ac.uk/undergraduate/ourreputation/distinguishedalumni/nemonemetaxas|work=University of Manchester website|title=Nemone Metaxas|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925224859/http://www.manchester.ac.uk/undergraduate/ourreputation/distinguishedalumni/nemonemetaxas|archive-date=25 September 2008}}</ref> Nemone worked as a [[research assistant]] in a [[psychiatric ward]]. She went on to become a receptionist at [[Kiss 102]] in Manchester. In 1997, she became the presenter and producer of ''The Word'' radio programme as [[Kiss 105]] went on the air. She subsequently presented [[Capital Manchester|Galaxy 102]] FM's Morning Show, Network Chill Out Show and The [[Galaxy Radio|Galaxy]] Chart for [[Manchester]]. She left as anchor of the Morning Show for a job at BBC Radio 1.\n \nNemone joined [[BBC Radio 1]] in October 2000 initially hosting the Saturday breakfast show. She filled in for [[Jo Whiley]]'s weekday morning show in 2001 while Whiley was on maternity leave. She then took the weekend afternoon slot which she hosted from Autumn 2001 through to the end of 2003.\n\nAfter a revamp of the Radio 1 daytime schedule from early 2004, Nemone replaced [[Scott Mills]] on the overnight show (4{{nbsp}}am{{snd}}7{{nbsp}}am) broadcasting to audiences in excess of 3 million. She left Radio 1 in September 2005; [[JK and Joel]] (Monday-Thursday) and [[Fearne Cotton]] and [[Reggie Yates]] (Friday) took over her early morning slot.\n\nShe joined [[BBC Radio 6 Music]] on 3 October 2005, she began presenting the ''[[Dream Ticket]]'' show as well as filling in on 6 Music's drive time show when [[Steve Lamacq]] was away.\n\nNemone took over [[Vic McGlynn]]'s weekday lunchtime show, weekdays in the 3{{snd}}4{{nbsp}}pm slot on 4 September 2006. She could also be heard covering various shows on [[BBC Radio 2]].\n\n[[Cerys Matthews]] filled in for her after she began six months maternity leave on 6 July 2009. After Matthews herself went on maternity leave on 24 November, the show was presented by either [[Chris Hawkins]] or [[Andrew Collins (broadcaster)|Andrew Collins]]. In July 2009, Nemone gave birth to a baby girl and returned to the station on 1 February 2010.\n\nWhen pregnant with her second child in 2011, she moved from weekdays taking over the weekend breakfast show.  After a short maternity leave she returned, steering it to record RAJAR figures.\n\nThe requirement to take the show to Media City in Salford meant Nemone passing on the opportunity of returning to Manchester; electing to stay in London where she had established her young family.\n\nIn April 2013 Nemone fulfilled a lifelong ambition to curate a specialist dance and electronic music show on BBC Radio 6 Music \u2013 ''Nemone's Electric Ladyland''. She runs a club night in West London.\n\nShe participated with her daughter in the Bumps & Babies Mile in [[Battersea Park]] for [[Sport Relief 2010]] along with [[Denise Van Outen]], [[Carly Cole]], [[Gail Emms]], [[Natasha Kaplinsky]] and [[Kim Medcalf]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sportrelief/news/180210_bumpsbabies.shtml|title=BBC \u2013 Sport Relief \u2013 Bumps and Babies Mile|work=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/02/19/bump-in-the-white-115875-22053881/|title=Carly Zucker joins Denise Van Outen on Sports Relief Bumps and Babies Mile in London|work=[[Daily Mirror]]|date=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Television career==\nNemone co-hosted the [[BBC One]] television programme ''[[101 Ways to Leave a Gameshow]]'' alongside [[Steve Jones (presenter)|Steve Jones]]. She was seen describing the method of eviction from the game show and then interviewing the losing contestants.\n\nNemone was one of the contestants on ''[[Celebrity Mastermind]]'' aired on 20 August 2017 on BBC One. Her specialist subject was the children's books of [[Roald Dahl]], and she came 2nd in the show.\n\n==Musical career==\nNemone is an accomplished musician. She was singer and saxophonist in a [[funk]] band \u2013 other members being Tom Findlay (who went on to form [[Groove Armada]]),<ref>stated by Nemone, herself, on-air, The Dream Ticket show, 19 January 2006.</ref> Andy Spence from NYPC, and Perrier Award-winning comedian [[Dan Antopolski]].\n\n==Athletic career==\nApart from radio and TV broadcasting, Nemone is also a keen athlete. Nemone is a former champion [[400 metres]] runner. In 1999 she won the Greater Manchester Championships. In 2000 she qualified for the British Championships, and competed in the 400m British Olympic trials.\n\nNemone decided to bid to run for the Greek Olympic team for the [[2004 Summer Olympics]]. Her training was filmed for the [[BBC Three]] television programme ''My Big Fat Greek Olympic Dream''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/4a5d9f9462224e68885bcc9213d6550c|work=BBC website|title=My Big Fat Greek Olympic Dream|date=1 August 2004}}</ref> She has competed in triathlons, most notably finishing in the top 20 amateur women in the 2006 London Triathlon.\n\nAlso, on screen, Nemone has hosted the [[X Games]] in Barcelona and Ski Sunday in [[Livigno]] for the television show ''[[Grandstand (TV series)|Grandstand]]''.\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*Honeyball, Lee,[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/osm/story/0,,502093,00.html \"My team : Radio 1 DJ Nemone Metaxas on Sale Harriers Athletics Club\"], [[The Observer]] Sport Monthly, Sunday 3 June 2001\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=2932430|name=Nemone}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01s9ky3 ''Nemone's Electric Ladyland''] (BBC Radio 6 Music)\n\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English radio DJs]]\n[[Category:People from Chester]]\n[[Category:English people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 1 presenters]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 2 presenters]]\n[[Category:BBC Radio 6 Music presenters]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSteve Jones(link changed toSteve Jones (Welsh presenter)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nemone"}
